I could not hold my annual Chap Goh Mei dinner with community leaders and other guests this year because of COVID-19. Instead, I spoke to a small audience at NTUC Auditorium, while groups joined us from 126 other locations virtually.

I took stock of our COVID-19 situation. We want to maintain our current stable position and get Singaporeans vaccinated quickly. The vaccines will take us one big step forward, but not back to business as usual, as many countries will not complete their vaccinations within this year. We have to live with the virus for many more years to come, maybe even permanently.

I also shared my thoughts on our external situation, and the outlook for the future. The next few years will not be easy. We canâ€™t tell exactly how the world will change after the pandemic, but as long as we work together, hold fast to our principles, and keep faith both with our pioneers as well as generations yet unborn, we will emerge stronger and thrive for many years to come. â€“ LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Chwee)

Our vaccination programme is proceeding smoothly. The latest delivery will allow us to continue as planned. More vaccination centres will open soon across Singapore. I hope seniors will book their appointments when their turn comes, so that we can all stay protected together.

â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The Year of the Ox brings new hope. Our national vaccination programme is progressing. Please take the vaccine when your turn comes â€“ both for yourself, and  your loved ones too.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Let us also give heartfelt thanks to the essential workers keeping Singapore going through the festive period, as well as our Malay, Indian and Eurasian friends who will be covering for their Chinese colleagues.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
You can read my Chinese New Year Message 2021 (in English and Mandarin) on the PMO website at go.gov.sg/cny2021pm. I wish all Singaporeans good health, and a very happy Chinese New Year. â€“ LHLâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €

(MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

description:
The recent community cases remind us that the war against COVID-19 is far from over. With Chinese New Year coming up, we have decided to tighten up to keep everyone safe.

These stricter measures will surely disappoint all of us looking forward to celebrating CNY. But just look at the countries near and far experiencing repeated surges in cases, and you will see why we need to stay vigilant.

Itâ€™s exactly 1 year since our first confirmed COVID-19 case in Singapore. The year has gone by at breakneck pace, as we all struggled to cope with the unprecedented chaos and disruption to our lives. Through immense effort and sacrifice, weâ€™ve got ourselves to a stable situation. Our vaccination programme is underway, with  seniors starting to get their shots next week.

Let us continue to protect ourselves and our loved ones by adhering to all the measures. â€“ LHL

(@straits_times Infographic)

These awards recognise the studentsâ€™ academic efforts and successes at school, and equally important, their character and their contributions to the community. Congratulations to everyone! We are proud of your achievements, more so in this tremendously challenging year.

The rainy afternoon yesterday did not dampen the joy of our Teck Ghee Edusave Awards recipients! We usually have a bigger celebration, but with the pandemic we had to scale down and space out, to hold this event safely.

These awards recognise the studentsâ€™ academic efforts and successes at school, and equally important, their character and their contributions to the community. Congratulations to everyone! We are proud of your achievements, more so in this tremendously challenging year.

Also happy to report that Iâ€™m feeling fine after my COVID-19 vaccination on Friday. Encouraged the parents who accompanied their kids to go for the vaccine when their turn comes! â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by LH Goh and Lee Jia Wen)

description:
Was at Singapore General Hospital (@sghseen) this morning to take a look at the start of COVID-19 vaccinations for healthcare workers from public institutions today. I also got my first dose of the jab!

It was quite painless, with the tiny needle and the steady hands of Senior Staff Nurse Fatimah Mohd Shah. I was observed for 30 minutes after getting the vaccine but I am happy to report that I feel fine and have no side effects.

I am confident that the vaccine is safe and effective. We will have ample vaccines for everyone, so I hope Singaporeans and long-term residents will get vaccinated when your turn comes, and help keep everyone safer. â€“ LHL

([1,2,4,5] MCI Photo by Fyrol; [3] Photo by me)

comments: Proud of you sir ğŸ™ thank you for your leadership

I am confident that the vaccine is safe and effective. We will have ample vaccines for everyone, so I hope Singaporeans and long-term residents will get vaccinated when your turn comes, and help keep everyone safer. â€“ LHL

Was at Singapore General Hospital (@sghseen) this morning to take a look at the start of COVID-19 vaccinations for healthcare workers from public institutions today. I also got my first dose of the jab!

It was quite painless, with the tiny needle and the steady hands of Senior Staff Nurse Fatimah Mohd Shah. I was observed for 30 minutes after getting the vaccine but I am happy to report that I feel fine and have no side effects.

I am confident that the vaccine is safe and effective. We will have ample vaccines for everyone, so I hope Singaporeans and long-term residents will get vaccinated when your turn comes, and help keep everyone safer. â€“ LHL

([1,2,4,5] MCI Photo by Fyrol; [3] Photo by me)

comments: That's great Sir. Is that Vaccine from Pfizer or Oxford/AstraZeneca..? Plz confirm Sir.

description:
Today we began COVID-19 vaccinations, with 30+ healthcare workers at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases. It marks a new chapter in our fight against the pandemic. 
 
In the coming weeks, the vaccine will be rolled out to more healthcare institutions. We will begin vaccinating the elderly from February. Thereafter we will do other Singaporeans and long-term residents who are eligible for vaccination.
 
The vaccine is key to living in a COVID-19 world, but it will still be some time before this storm will pass. Meanwhile, letâ€™s stay vigilant to keep ourselves and our loved ones healthy and safe. â€“ LHL

The Multi-Ministry Taskforce will announce details of the rollout in due course, so do stay tuned. We are prioritising our healthcare workers and the elderly. Vaccination will be voluntary, but I encourage Singaporeans to take the vaccine. 

Itâ€™s been a long and arduous year. I hope that this news will give Singaporeans cheer this festive season, and reason to be optimistic for 2021. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Betty Chua)

It has been a long year. But because of our collective efforts against COVID-19, we are ready to ease into Phase 3 on 28 December. This is possible because of all of you who made many sacrifices, so that our numbers and situation are now under control.

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. â€“ LHL

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)

description:
It has been a long year. But because of our collective efforts against COVID-19, we are ready to ease into Phase 3 on 28 December. This is possible because of all of you who made many sacrifices, so that our numbers and situation are now under control.

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. â€“ LHL

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. â€“ LHL

A big thank you to all our workers for your contributions to Singapore, especially during COVID-19.
2020 has been a year like no other. Many workers have had their wages and livelihoods affected by the pandemic, particularly those in hard-hit sectors. Frontline and essential workers have made many sacrifices, to keep their families and all of us safe.

We do not know when this pandemic will end, but thereâ€™s light at the end of the tunnel. Weâ€™re closer to getting a vaccine, and starting to reopen our borders. In the meantime, stay safe and stay strong. 
During this pandemic, labour MPs have been working overtime helping union workers, while the Air Transport Executive Staff Union has been working with SIA and other airlines to assist ground staff and protect their interests. Therefore, I nominate NTUC Assistant Secretary-General @patricktaytg and President of the AESU Daniel Loh to show your appreciation next! â€“ LHL
#toast2U #toast2Uchallenge
-------------------------------------------------
For every #toast2U hashtag, NTUC Income will pledge $2 to the NTUC U Care Fund, which helps low-income members and their families through various assistance programmes to defray their cost of living and childrenâ€™s school expenses, as well as members whose livelihood had been affected by Covid-19.
When nominated:
1. All you need to do is record yourself â€œreceivingâ€ the drink from the person who nominated you and give a toast accompanied by a note of appreciation in the post.
2. â€œPassâ€ the drink on by nominating two others.
3. Tag @UHeartsg for us to keep track of the donations, and remember to make your post public!
This @UHeartsg initiative is by @nebosg and @young.ntuc, supported by NTUC Income.

description:
Glad to have spoken with Japanese Prime Minister @suga.yoshihide over the phone this afternoon. We discussed strengthening cooperation between our countries amidst the COVID-19 pandemic, and welcomed the resumption of essential travel between Singapore and Japan. 

Singapore and Japan are like-minded partners enjoying a longstanding close relationship. We have many opportunities to work together, e.g. in vaccine multilateralism, third-country infrastructure cooperation, and preparing for the digital economy. We also both support multilateralism and are working to sign the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership by the end of this year. 

I look forward to partnering Prime Minister Suga to strengthen ties between our countries, and hope to meet him in person soon. â€“ LHL

(PMO Photo by Alex Qiu)

comments: Yes sir hope we could foster a stronger bilateral relationship

Singapore has been doing our part collecting and analysing data on the coronavirus, in order to better understand this new threat. But our efforts alone are not enough. A global pandemic requires a coordinated global response, especially in scientific research and government actions. â €
â €
Speaking to the virtual #GlobalGoalUnite Summit by @glblctzn, I emphasised the importance of vaccine multilateralism in our common fight against COVID-19.â €
â €
Singapore looks forward to working with the @europeancommission and like-minded countries, as well as the @who, Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations (CEPI), and @gavialliance, to develop vaccines and distribute them fairly and expeditiously to people in all countries. â €
â €
The search for vaccines may take some time, but we will maximise our chances of tackling COVID-19 by working together. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

Singapore has been doing our part collecting and analysing data on the coronavirus, in order to better understand this new threat. But our efforts alone are not enough. A global pandemic requires a coordinated global response, especially in scientific research and government actions. â €
â €
Speaking to the virtual #GlobalGoalUnite Summit by @glblctzn, I emphasised the importance of vaccine multilateralism in our common fight against COVID-19.â €
â €
Singapore looks forward to working with the @europeancommission and like-minded countries, as well as the @who, Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations (CEPI), and @gavialliance, to develop vaccines and distribute them fairly and expeditiously to people in all countries. â €
â €
The search for vaccines may take some time, but we will maximise our chances of tackling COVID-19 by working together. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

description:
Had a good discussion with fellow leaders at the virtual 36th @asean Summit today.â €
â €
In my intervention, I spoke about strengthening cooperation by sharing technologies to contain the COVID-19 pandemic, working as a region to procure an equitable, steady and affordable supply of treatments and vaccines, and upholding the international trading system and maintaining supply chain connectivity.â €
â €
How we respond to this crisis will decide whether #ASEAN forges ahead of the competition or falls behind. We must stand united to overcome the challenges ahead, enhance regional economic integration, and work towards the long-term safety and prosperity of the region.â €
â €
My thanks to Vietnam for hosting a successful virtual summit during this unprecedented time. I look forward to our next meeting at the ASEAN Summit this year. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#WeAreASEANâ €
#ASEAN2020

COVID-19 has been a forceful reminder of the necessity for countries to mount a united response to common threats like the pandemic and climate change.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The Global Vaccine Summit is a donor pledging conference to fund the immunisation of children in poor countries against deadly but preventable diseases. But in the time of COVID-19, yesterdayâ€™s virtual event, which was co-hosted by the UK government and @gavialliance, was also an opportunity for countries to come together to coordinate efforts to develop and produce a COVID-19 vaccine. You can watch the video on my Facebook Page.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was invited to share Singaporeâ€™s efforts in this endeavour. Aside from our US$13 million contribution towards international efforts to combat the virus, we are investing in R&D on diagnostics, vaccines and therapeutics, as well as building up our vaccine manufacturing capacity.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
We are all in the same fight together and Singapore will do our part in this global call for action. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)

comments: Dear sir, SG strategyâ€™s COVID needs to be revised: it is not possible to have 0 community cases. We live in a globalized world and soon the borders will reopen.The aim always should have been to flatten the curve (i.e. not to overburden hospitals). We achieved that a long time ago, and hospitals and ICUs have plenty of space to treat the most severe cases. With all due respect, sir, we are fighting the wrong battle.Let the economy restart faster, and letâ€™s do to phase 2 and phase 3. The long term consequences will be much more severe than having around 10 community cases a day, mostly with mild symptoms. Dengue has killed 12 people in SG, coronavirus 24, in 2020. Other diseases are being forgotten amidst this Covid crisis.

â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The Global Vaccine Summit is a donor pledging conference to fund the immunisation of children in poor countries against deadly but preventable diseases. But in the time of COVID-19, yesterdayâ€™s virtual event, which was co-hosted by the UK government and @gavialliance, was also an opportunity for countries to come together to coordinate efforts to develop and produce a COVID-19 vaccine. You can watch the video on my Facebook Page.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was invited to share Singaporeâ€™s efforts in this endeavour. Aside from our US$13 million contribution towards international efforts to combat the virus, we are investing in R&D on diagnostics, vaccines and therapeutics, as well as building up our vaccine manufacturing capacity.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
We are all in the same fight together and Singapore will do our part in this global call for action. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI Photo by Chwee)

Tomorrow, we will be lifting some circuit breaker measures. A big relief to all, but certainly not without its risks.

The number of daily cases in the community has come down considerably. More patients have now recovered and been discharged, than are still receiving care. But COVID-19 is far from defeated.

I know many of you are looking forward to seeing your friends in school again, or visiting parents and grandparents. But we must remain cautious and vigilant.

Please keep your guard up. Maintain safe distancing, wear masks when outdoors and at work, watch your personal hygiene and wash hands frequently. Avoid crowds and gatherings. If we all do this, then life can go on more or less normally after the circuit breaker. We donâ€™t want COVID-19 cases to spike up again, and be forced to tighten up once more.

Dealing with COVID-19 is a marathon, not a sprint. Even after a vaccine is found, everything will not simply go back to the way it was before. COVID-19 has exposed how vulnerable our way of life is. But it has also given us the opportunity to prove our mettle, and come back stronger.

As we end this circuit breaker, I thank everyone again for playing your part, so that we can now reopen safely. We must all keep at it together. Do not allow the sacrifices of our healthcare workers and others who have kept Singapore running to be in vain. â€“ LHL

Tomorrow, we will be lifting some circuit breaker measures. A big relief to all, but certainly not without its risks.

The number of daily cases in the community has come down considerably. More patients have now recovered and been discharged, than are still receiving care. But COVID-19 is far from defeated.

I know many of you are looking forward to seeing your friends in school again, or visiting parents and grandparents. But we must remain cautious and vigilant.

Please keep your guard up. Maintain safe distancing, wear masks when outdoors and at work, watch your personal hygiene and wash hands frequently. Avoid crowds and gatherings. If we all do this, then life can go on more or less normally after the circuit breaker. We donâ€™t want COVID-19 cases to spike up again, and be forced to tighten up once more.

Dealing with COVID-19 is a marathon, not a sprint. Even after a vaccine is found, everything will not simply go back to the way it was before. COVID-19 has exposed how vulnerable our way of life is. But it has also given us the opportunity to prove our mettle, and come back stronger.

As we end this circuit breaker, I thank everyone again for playing your part, so that we can now reopen safely. We must all keep at it together. Do not allow the sacrifices of our healthcare workers and others who have kept Singapore running to be in vain. â€“ LHL

The number of daily cases in the community has come down considerably. More patients have now recovered and been discharged, than are still receiving care. But COVID-19 is far from defeated.

I know many of you are looking forward to seeing your friends in school again, or visiting parents and grandparents. But we must remain cautious and vigilant.

Please keep your guard up. Maintain safe distancing, wear masks when outdoors and at work, watch your personal hygiene and wash hands frequently. Avoid crowds and gatherings. If we all do this, then life can go on more or less normally after the circuit breaker. We donâ€™t want COVID-19 cases to spike up again, and be forced to tighten up once more.

Dealing with COVID-19 is a marathon, not a sprint. Even after a vaccine is found, everything will not simply go back to the way it was before. COVID-19 has exposed how vulnerable our way of life is. But it has also given us the opportunity to prove our mettle, and come back stronger.

As we end this circuit breaker, I thank everyone again for playing your part, so that we can now reopen safely. We must all keep at it together. Do not allow the sacrifices of our healthcare workers and others who have kept Singapore running to be in vain. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

Please keep your guard up. Maintain safe distancing, wear masks when outdoors and at work, watch your personal hygiene and wash hands frequently. Avoid crowds and gatherings. If we all do this, then life can go on more or less normally after the circuit breaker. We donâ€™t want COVID-19 cases to spike up again, and be forced to tighten up once more.

Dealing with COVID-19 is a marathon, not a sprint. Even after a vaccine is found, everything will not simply go back to the way it was before. COVID-19 has exposed how vulnerable our way of life is. But it has also given us the opportunity to prove our mettle, and come back stronger.

As we end this circuit breaker, I thank everyone again for playing your part, so that we can now reopen safely. We must all keep at it together. Do not allow the sacrifices of our healthcare workers and others who have kept Singapore running to be in vain. â€“ LHL

Held a virtual summit with New Zealand PM @jacindaardern today. Since our last call nearly two months ago, our countries have moved from strict circuit breaking measures to a gradual, careful easing of restrictions. We talked about technological solutions and shared our strategies, including possible collaboration on vaccine development.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was pleased to mark the one-year anniversary of the Singapore-New Zealand Enhanced Partnership, and look forward to expanding our cooperation with new initiatives that both sides value. During the global pandemic, we have spoken up against protectionism and for keeping supply chains intact. Earlier in April, we received 20 tonnes of New Zealandâ€™s fine produce, while New Zealand received medical supplies on the return journey.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The times are challenging, but we are dealing with the problems one by one, and planning ahead. As part of safe reopening, we are discussing creating a green lane for short-term essential travel between our countries. I hope this works out, and it will not be long before PM Ardern and I can meet in person again. â€“ LHL

Held a virtual summit with New Zealand PM @jacindaardern today. Since our last call nearly two months ago, our countries have moved from strict circuit breaking measures to a gradual, careful easing of restrictions. We talked about technological solutions and shared our strategies, including possible collaboration on vaccine development.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was pleased to mark the one-year anniversary of the Singapore-New Zealand Enhanced Partnership, and look forward to expanding our cooperation with new initiatives that both sides value. During the global pandemic, we have spoken up against protectionism and for keeping supply chains intact. Earlier in April, we received 20 tonnes of New Zealandâ€™s fine produce, while New Zealand received medical supplies on the return journey.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The times are challenging, but we are dealing with the problems one by one, and planning ahead. As part of safe reopening, we are discussing creating a green lane for short-term essential travel between our countries. I hope this works out, and it will not be long before PM Ardern and I can meet in person again. â€“ LHL

Held a virtual summit with New Zealand PM @jacindaardern today. Since our last call nearly two months ago, our countries have moved from strict circuit breaking measures to a gradual, careful easing of restrictions. We talked about technological solutions and shared our strategies, including possible collaboration on vaccine development.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was pleased to mark the one-year anniversary of the Singapore-New Zealand Enhanced Partnership, and look forward to expanding our cooperation with new initiatives that both sides value. During the global pandemic, we have spoken up against protectionism and for keeping supply chains intact. Earlier in April, we received 20 tonnes of New Zealandâ€™s fine produce, while New Zealand received medical supplies on the return journey.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The times are challenging, but we are dealing with the problems one by one, and planning ahead. As part of safe reopening, we are discussing creating a green lane for short-term essential travel between our countries. I hope this works out, and it will not be long before PM Ardern and I can meet in person again. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI Photo by Zinkie Aw)

comments: Dear Sir, please do not only consider resuming business as essential travel. Families, lovers and other important relations have been cruelly split apart by travel bans. If there's one thing we can learn from NZ, it is to apply empathy during these difficult times and not just focus on outcomes that are easy to measure.

comments: Feedback from a Pro Govt supporter : it takes an individual Razer Tan Min-Liang to do this : Produce our own masks (a couple of millions masks each month). Finally someone with "great common sense" is doing it. My question is : what are our human resources-rich Govt doing all this while ? What are our top civil servants doing ? What are our agencies EDB TDB A*STAR MTI doing all this while since Feb 18 when Minister Lawrence Wong was mooting with the idea of producing our own masks?. You are a very good Prime Minister. Lawrence is a good & hardworking Minister. But a couple of million masks a month may not be enough. Can our Govt support Razer in (1) help him to expedite in setting up the factory with our "Govt agencies" rich resources and industrial contacts (2) our Govt to chip in and ramp up the production scale to at least 15  mil to 30 mil masks a month. This will help create some jobs too. This will help "boost confidence" if people are going out in public and our Govt to enforce "All to Wear Masks" when in public places, in view of the heightened risks as compared to Jan situation. Especially in MRTs, Buses, Supermarkets etc *News Recap 1 : ST 19 Feb : SINGAPORE - Singapore is looking for new sources of supply for masks and developing capabilities to manufacture them locally as other Asian countries clamp down on mask exports, Minister for National Development Lawrence Wong has said."In recent weeks, some places like Taiwan, Thailand and India have banned or tightened regulations on the export of masks," he said in a written parliamentary reply on Tuesday (Feb 18). *News Recap 2 : CNA 1 Apr : SINGAPORE: Singapore gaming company Razer announced plans on Wednesday (Apr 1) to set up an automated face mask manufacturing line within 30 days to produce "a couple of million certified masks" each month. Not least, thank you Mr Tan Min Liang. Thank you Mr Lee and Lawrence Wong too for ur good leadership & hardwork. @leehsienloong@lawrencewongst@khawboonwan @minliangtan

comments: FEEDBACK/SHARING OF WORLD NEWS : latest news (CNN) : (QUOTE) Austria "The wearing of face masks in supermarkets will become compulsory from Wednesday, Austrian Chancellor Sebastian Kurz announced.''As of the moment these masks are handed out in front of the supermarkets and it will become compulsory to wear them in supermarkets'', Kurz said, adding that ''the goal is in the medium term to not only wear these masks in supermarkets but also more generally wherever people have contact with each other''Â " . (UNQUOTE) It is our Govt's job to do it (ensuring enough masks for the people to wear in public e.g. in crowded mrts and buses). Whether is it buying from China or setting up a factory to produce masks, just do it. Wearing masks definitely is effective in the overall containment efforts. You cannot have 1 good measure in say foodcourts distancing control and then "overlook or fail" in another area : e.g. mrt , buses. If so, the overall containment efforts will not be as effective. @leehsienloong@lawrencewongst@khawboonwan @gankimyong @ongyekung @teocheehean So in my opinion, our Govt have done a good job in many areas but "overlook, fail or loophole" in other areas. This is not good enough for the overall containment effectiveness.

â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Like the rest of the world, I hope that a treatment or vaccine will happen sooner than later. But we must be psychologically prepared for a long battle ahead, and learn to live with the virus by adjusting our routines and adopting new norms.
